x4freetext: See for corrections.
A systematic study of (n,p) reactions at 14.7 MeV
The Karlsruhe Cyclotron was used for
the deuteron  breakup neutrons.
-No details given for the 14.7 MeV data.
For the 14.7 MeV data.
Flux densities were (1-3)E+09 neutrons per cm**2
and second.
Fast neutrons were produced by bombarding a
1cm thick Be-target with 30MeV deuterons at 2 microA
current, measured by a Faraday cup.
-Isotopic enrichment  ,%  :
28-Ni-58 -natural
23-V-51 -natural
26-Fe-58 -natural
28-Ni-62 -natural
In all other cases high purity samples of natural
isotopic abundances were used. Purity more 99.99% .
Targets materials were sealed in polyethylene bags,
sandwiched between two layers of flux monitor
material of Al or As2-O3 .
No fast pneumatic system used (comment
from Prof. S.M.Qaim)
For the reactions 49Ti(N,P)49Sc, 63Cu(N,P)63Ni,
beta-counting were performed.
Modern methods of chemical separation were
employed, wherever necessary- Cu-63(n,p), I-127((n,p).
Gamma-and X-ray-spectroscopy were employed.
Gamma-gamma coincidence.
Co-axial 28 cm**3 GeLi detector in case of
very low energy gamma-rays, or Ge detector of active
area 2 cm**2 with thin beryllium window.
A low-background anticoincidence beta-
proportional counter.

for 49Ti(N,P)49Sc, 63Cu(N,P)63Ni.
-The systematics of the cross sections were discussed
in comparison with data from other authors.
-Cross section data taken from Conference
Proceedings, and from Reference NP/A,283,269.
Usual corrections for:
- Decay,
- Gamma-transition intensities,
- Internal conversion coefficients,
- Counting efficiency,
- Geometry,
- Absorption.
Between 6 and 15 % were the errors.
Updated with Ref. NP/A,283,269.
Adding MONITOR data to resp. SUBWORK and
adding modifier SPA to resp. REACTION strings.

corrected to include also ND-contribution.

Data of Table 2 of 76GARMISH are restored in Subents
initially and according to archive file).

x4freetext: Measured effective cross-section for wide neutron
spectrum. Averaging in neutron energy rage > EN-MIN .
Deuteron break-up spectrum has an approximate
Maxwellian shape with a maximum intensity at 11.5 MeV.
The shape of spectrum calculated by the method of
Schmidt and Muenzel is in Fig.1 of 76GARMIS.
EN-MIN about 2.0 MeV.
EN-MAX about 28. MeV .
Neutron flux densities obtained via the two methods
were found to be almost identical.
